05228nam a22008055i 9789048521050DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20092008ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485210507 a10.1515/97890485210502doi  a(DE-B1597)517689  a(OCoLC)751962326  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a338.094891 aFutselaar, Ralf, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLard, Lice and Longevity :bThe Standard of Living in Occupied Denmark and the Netherlands, 1940-1945 /cHsieh Ying-Hui, Ralf Futselaar; ed. by W. Koetsenruijter, J. de Jong. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Netherlands Institute for War Documentation00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Small States in a Total War -- tChapter 3. The Mystery of the Dying Dutch -- tChapter 4. Feeding the People -- tChapter 5. From Riches to Rags -- tChapter 6. Value for Money -- tChapter 7. Poverty in Moneyed Times -- tChapter 8. The Shadow Economy -- tChapter 9. Filth, food and infectious disease mortality -- tChapter 10. Conclusion -- tA note on archival sources and abbreviations -- tAppendix I -- tAppendix II -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLard, Lice and Longevity reconstructs economic policies implemented in Denmark and the Netherlands during the German occupation. It clearly shows that the experiences of both these countries during World War I, and during the 1930s equipped them to introduce extensive and intrusive economic controls to ward off a subsistence crisis. In spite of the strong similarities between the two countries in terms of policies and economic order, there remains a glaring difference between the two. Throughout the occupation years, the Netherlands suffered a markedly higher level of child mortality than before or after the war, caused by an upsurge of infectious diseases. Child health in Denmark, on the other hand, declined during the occupation years, and infectious diseases rose only marginally there. In spite of similar policies, hence, the outcome in terms of the biological standard of living was dissimilar. By closely investigating the impact of various policies on everyday life, and the amounts of goods available to different groups of consumers, this study identifies the causes of this remarkable divergence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCost and standard of livingzDenmark. 0aCost and standard of livingzNetherlands. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zDenmark. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zNetherlands. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aKoetsenruijter, W., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYing-Hui, Hsieh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 ade Jong, J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311070067108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311102378608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z97831106627880 cprintz978905260253040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048521050?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048521050423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048521050/original  a978-3-11-060651-5  AUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066278-8  Amsterdam Univers